1
00:00:00,060 --> 00:00:02,400
If you don't want to
be like everyone else,

2
00:00:02,400 --> 00:00:04,770
then you have to avoid the
number one wealth killer

3
00:00:04,770 --> 00:00:06,150
that nobody talks about.

4
00:00:06,150 --> 00:00:07,590
Take a look at this chart,

5
00:00:07,590 --> 00:00:09,270
it shows how the average person

6
00:00:09,270 --> 00:00:11,040
spends their money each month,

7
00:00:11,040 --> 00:00:12,180
and believe it or not,

8
00:00:12,180 --> 00:00:15,090
one of these categories is
quietly killing your chances

9
00:00:15,090 --> 00:00:15,990
of building wealth.

10
00:00:15,990 --> 00:00:17,490
So let's uncover it together.

11
00:00:17,490 --> 00:00:19,320
First up, housing.

12
00:00:19,320 --> 00:00:21,180
This is the biggest slice of the pie,

13
00:00:21,180 --> 00:00:23,520
so it's definitely the
wealth killer, right?

14
00:00:23,520 --> 00:00:27,120
Well, although paying rent
or a mortgage is expensive,

15
00:00:27,120 --> 00:00:28,170
at least it provides you

16
00:00:28,170 --> 00:00:29,250
with a place to live.

17
00:00:29,250 --> 00:00:32,880
Next, taxes, nobody likes these.

18
00:00:32,880 --> 00:00:35,520
Well, unless your name
happens to be Gary Stevenson,

19
00:00:35,520 --> 00:00:36,990
but let's not get into that.

20
00:00:36,990 --> 00:00:40,830
Next, utilities and household expenses,

21
00:00:40,830 --> 00:00:42,090
they're not fun to pay,

22
00:00:42,090 --> 00:00:44,430
but you can easily get
them down by calling around

23
00:00:44,430 --> 00:00:45,540
for the best deals.

24
00:00:45,540 --> 00:00:47,400
How about all of these?

25
00:00:47,400 --> 00:00:49,590
There are so many of
these little expenses,

26
00:00:49,590 --> 00:00:51,270
but most of them are flexible,

27
00:00:51,270 --> 00:00:53,790
so that leaves us with one section left.

28
00:00:53,790 --> 00:00:55,920
Can you guess what it is?

29
00:00:55,920 --> 00:00:58,140
Transportation; car payments,

30
00:00:58,140 --> 00:01:01,890
insurance, fuel, repairs, parking,

31
00:01:01,890 --> 00:01:05,730
all for something that goes
down in value every single day.

32
00:01:05,730 --> 00:01:09,180
The average new car costs nearly $48,000.

33
00:01:09,180 --> 00:01:12,060
It's not an investment, it's
not building your wealth,

34
00:01:12,060 --> 00:01:13,290
and in most cases

35
00:01:13,290 --> 00:01:15,720
it's just a financial
black hole on wheels.

36
00:01:15,720 --> 00:01:18,630
That's why out of all of these expenses,

37
00:01:18,630 --> 00:01:21,560
transportation, specifically your car,

38
00:01:21,560 --> 00:01:23,370
is the number one wealth killer

39
00:01:23,370 --> 00:01:24,977
and it's only getting worse.

40
00:01:24,977 --> 00:01:27,360
(eerie music)

41
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:29,310
There's been an absolute explosion

42
00:01:29,310 --> 00:01:31,590
in the amount of money
people are on their cars.

43
00:01:31,590 --> 00:01:34,230
It's honestly getting outta control.

44
00:01:34,230 --> 00:01:35,580
Let me show you what I mean.

45
00:01:35,580 --> 00:01:40,417
In 2005, total auto loan debt
was sitting at $720 billion.

46
00:01:41,880 --> 00:01:45,480
Five years later it reached $850 billion.

47
00:01:45,480 --> 00:01:47,640
Fast forward to 2020,

48
00:01:47,640 --> 00:01:51,210
it's rocketed all the
way up to 1.38 trillion,

49
00:01:51,210 --> 00:01:54,900
and in 2025 we're sat at an all time high

50
00:01:54,900 --> 00:01:57,630
of $1.62 trillion.

51
00:01:57,630 --> 00:01:59,370
This has led to more people than ever

52
00:01:59,370 --> 00:02:02,520
being what I like to call car poor.

53
00:02:02,520 --> 00:02:04,140
This is when you're making just enough

54
00:02:04,140 --> 00:02:05,730
to cover your car payments,

55
00:02:05,730 --> 00:02:08,220
but not enough to build
wealth at the same time.

56
00:02:08,220 --> 00:02:10,290
It's like you're trapped on a treadmill

57
00:02:10,290 --> 00:02:11,550
that never slows down,

58
00:02:11,550 --> 00:02:14,220
but why get on this
treadmill in the first place?

59
00:02:14,220 --> 00:02:17,160
Well, more people than
ever care about their image

60
00:02:17,160 --> 00:02:18,990
and driving a nice car

61
00:02:18,990 --> 00:02:21,600
is one of the quickest ways
to impress other people.

62
00:02:21,600 --> 00:02:24,750
The car industry spends billions
of dollars convincing you

63
00:02:24,750 --> 00:02:27,120
that a new car is gonna
transform your image,

64
00:02:27,120 --> 00:02:29,520
confidence and maybe even your love life.

65
00:02:29,520 --> 00:02:31,500
They don't show you
sitting in a traffic jam

66
00:02:31,500 --> 00:02:33,480
on a rainy Tuesday after getting slapped

67
00:02:33,480 --> 00:02:35,310
with a $600 repair bill.

68
00:02:35,310 --> 00:02:38,490
Clever marketing makes you
feel like success is finance,

69
00:02:38,490 --> 00:02:41,580
but really it's a liar being
fed to keep you trapped.

70
00:02:41,580 --> 00:02:43,140
Look at the cyber truck

71
00:02:43,140 --> 00:02:46,110
that wasn't sold on
practicality or daily use.

72
00:02:46,110 --> 00:02:48,210
It was sold on the image of power

73
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:50,790
and looking like you're
straight out of a sci-fi film.

74
00:02:50,790 --> 00:02:52,710
Social pressure fuels this too.

75
00:02:52,710 --> 00:02:55,380
Nobody claps when you drive
an old Honda that's paid off

76
00:02:55,380 --> 00:02:56,520
and running smoothly,

77
00:02:56,520 --> 00:02:59,910
but if you roll up in a
brand new BMW on finance,

78
00:02:59,910 --> 00:03:01,680
people tend to give you approval

79
00:03:01,680 --> 00:03:03,690
and assume you're doing
really well for yourself.

80
00:03:03,690 --> 00:03:05,670
I see so many young lads these days trying

81
00:03:05,670 --> 00:03:08,130
to look successful rather
than actually trying

82
00:03:08,130 --> 00:03:10,710
to be successful, especially in cultures

83
00:03:10,710 --> 00:03:13,020
where car ownership gives you credibility.

84
00:03:13,020 --> 00:03:16,620
This need to look rich, it's
what's causing this to happen.

85
00:03:16,620 --> 00:03:19,020
It makes people stretch
their money so thin

86
00:03:19,020 --> 00:03:21,270
that the car actually ends up owning them.

87
00:03:21,270 --> 00:03:24,240
This car poor trap gets
even worse for some people

88
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:27,180
as they borrow more than
the car is actually worth.

89
00:03:27,180 --> 00:03:29,580
It sounds silly and you might be thinking,

90
00:03:29,580 --> 00:03:31,200
why would anyone do that?

91
00:03:31,200 --> 00:03:33,090
But it's actually very common

92
00:03:33,090 --> 00:03:35,490
and it's called being in negative equity

93
00:03:35,490 --> 00:03:37,350
or upside down on the loan.

94
00:03:37,350 --> 00:03:39,510
In Q4 of 2023,

95
00:03:39,510 --> 00:03:42,390
nearly one in four people
were in this exact position,

96
00:03:42,390 --> 00:03:45,810
so this could result in
you owing $40,000 on a car

97
00:03:45,810 --> 00:03:48,270
that's only worth $30,000.

98
00:03:48,270 --> 00:03:51,330
This means your $10,000
in negative equity.

99
00:03:51,330 --> 00:03:53,370
I've actually had a lot of people email me

100
00:03:53,370 --> 00:03:55,650
after reading my free weekly newsletter

101
00:03:55,650 --> 00:03:58,230
saying it helped them
avoid traps like this

102
00:03:58,230 --> 00:03:59,940
and even make a bit of extra money

103
00:03:59,940 --> 00:04:01,740
with some of the strategies I share.

104
00:04:01,740 --> 00:04:03,330
Is something I just do for fun

105
00:04:03,330 --> 00:04:05,460
and I really enjoy reading the replies,

106
00:04:05,460 --> 00:04:07,680
so if you want me to send
you those emails too,

107
00:04:07,680 --> 00:04:09,450
I'll drop a link in the description.

108
00:04:09,450 --> 00:04:11,700
Anyway, if you want to
avoid being car poor

109
00:04:11,700 --> 00:04:12,750
like most people,

110
00:04:12,750 --> 00:04:14,700
then you need to
understand the true cost of

111
00:04:14,700 --> 00:04:17,896
that so-called affordable
car sitting in the showroom.

112
00:04:17,896 --> 00:04:20,370
(eerie music)

113
00:04:20,370 --> 00:04:22,620
I feel like a lot of
people don't understand

114
00:04:22,620 --> 00:04:26,070
that the sticker price of a
car is far from the true cost

115
00:04:26,070 --> 00:04:27,450
of owning that car.

116
00:04:27,450 --> 00:04:28,440
Let me explain.

117
00:04:28,440 --> 00:04:30,390
Take a look at this Honda Civic.

118
00:04:30,390 --> 00:04:32,190
It's the most commonly purchased car

119
00:04:32,190 --> 00:04:35,760
by people aged between
18 and 24 in America,

120
00:04:35,760 --> 00:04:38,880
and on the surface it looks
like a sensible choice.

121
00:04:38,880 --> 00:04:40,987
The sticker price is $27,867,

122
00:04:44,550 --> 00:04:45,870
which seems reasonable.

123
00:04:45,870 --> 00:04:48,360
However, let's dig into the true cost

124
00:04:48,360 --> 00:04:50,250
to own this car over five years.

125
00:04:50,250 --> 00:04:52,830
First up is depreciation,

126
00:04:52,830 --> 00:04:56,940
and on this car that's $10,999.

127
00:04:56,940 --> 00:04:59,430
This cost starts the second
you drive your new car

128
00:04:59,430 --> 00:05:02,400
off the lot as it drops 10 to 15% in value

129
00:05:02,400 --> 00:05:03,900
before you even make it home.

130
00:05:03,900 --> 00:05:05,010
Over five years,

131
00:05:05,010 --> 00:05:08,460
you'll lose nearly $11,000
to depreciation alone.

132
00:05:08,460 --> 00:05:09,293
Think about that.

133
00:05:09,293 --> 00:05:12,840
$11,000 just gone

134
00:05:12,840 --> 00:05:15,570
all because time passed
and your car got older.

135
00:05:15,570 --> 00:05:20,130
It's like paying $2,200
every year for the privilege

136
00:05:20,130 --> 00:05:21,840
of watching your money evaporate.

137
00:05:21,840 --> 00:05:24,330
Next is insurance.

138
00:05:24,330 --> 00:05:27,690
This is nearly $12,000 over five years,

139
00:05:27,690 --> 00:05:29,490
and that's a conservative estimate.

140
00:05:29,490 --> 00:05:31,740
This figure is based on a 40-year-old

141
00:05:31,740 --> 00:05:34,680
with a perfect credit
score and a clean record.

142
00:05:34,680 --> 00:05:35,850
If you are a young guy,

143
00:05:35,850 --> 00:05:38,160
then this number is actually much worse.

144
00:05:38,160 --> 00:05:39,780
You are probably looking at double that.

145
00:05:39,780 --> 00:05:41,310
Sure, you can get this down a bit

146
00:05:41,310 --> 00:05:44,250
by calling them every
single year, negotiating,

147
00:05:44,250 --> 00:05:46,590
and never staying loyal to one company,

148
00:05:46,590 --> 00:05:48,510
but it's still gonna be a high cost

149
00:05:48,510 --> 00:05:51,390
even if you do manage to get
a bit of a discount each year.

150
00:05:51,390 --> 00:05:53,317
Then there's fuel.

151
00:05:53,317 --> 00:05:57,750
$6,415, just to keep the thing moving.

152
00:05:57,750 --> 00:05:59,940
This is actually getting so expensive.

153
00:05:59,940 --> 00:06:02,460
Now for financing.

154
00:06:02,460 --> 00:06:04,837
This is the cost of not
having cash upfront.

155
00:06:04,837 --> 00:06:08,880
$4,719 over five years

156
00:06:08,880 --> 00:06:12,750
assumes you've got a decent
credit score and put down 10%,

157
00:06:12,750 --> 00:06:14,850
but if your credit score is bad,

158
00:06:14,850 --> 00:06:18,060
then you could be looking
at 15 to 20% interest rates

159
00:06:18,060 --> 00:06:21,030
instead of the six to
6.5% I'm showing here.

160
00:06:21,030 --> 00:06:23,340
That's why I always
drill home the importance

161
00:06:23,340 --> 00:06:26,550
of building up a good credit
score by having a credit card

162
00:06:26,550 --> 00:06:28,590
and putting small monthly expenses on it

163
00:06:28,590 --> 00:06:31,350
that you pay back in full
at the end of each month.

164
00:06:31,350 --> 00:06:33,420
This means you avoid paying any interest

165
00:06:33,420 --> 00:06:35,760
and prove that you're
a responsible borrower.

166
00:06:35,760 --> 00:06:38,617
Next up is maintenance.

167
00:06:38,617 --> 00:06:42,420
$3,224 over five years

168
00:06:42,420 --> 00:06:46,650
for oil changes, brake pads,
tires, the list goes on.

169
00:06:46,650 --> 00:06:48,900
However, you can do this a lot cheaper

170
00:06:48,900 --> 00:06:51,150
if you learn a little bit about cars.

171
00:06:51,150 --> 00:06:52,950
I used to race in car championships

172
00:06:52,950 --> 00:06:56,070
so I know the ins and outs of
how to fix stuff on my car.

173
00:06:56,070 --> 00:06:58,440
This has saved me
thousands over the years.

174
00:06:58,440 --> 00:07:00,780
I mean, if you learn
to change your own oil,

175
00:07:00,780 --> 00:07:04,050
you'll save 30 to $50 every single time,

176
00:07:04,050 --> 00:07:07,920
and if you buy a basic OBD
scanner for 20 to 30 bucks,

177
00:07:07,920 --> 00:07:10,290
you can diagnose most problems yourself

178
00:07:10,290 --> 00:07:12,900
instead of paying the
garage $100 just for them

179
00:07:12,900 --> 00:07:14,640
to plug it in and tell you what's wrong.

180
00:07:14,640 --> 00:07:17,070
Then taxes and fees.

181
00:07:17,070 --> 00:07:19,470
This is just the
government's cut, road tax,

182
00:07:19,470 --> 00:07:21,420
registration and inspection fees

183
00:07:21,420 --> 00:07:24,900
will come to around
$2,800 over five years.

184
00:07:24,900 --> 00:07:27,240
Finally, we've got repairs.

185
00:07:27,240 --> 00:07:31,590
We'll budget $1,790 for
this over five years.

186
00:07:31,590 --> 00:07:33,630
These surprise expenses are killers

187
00:07:33,630 --> 00:07:35,160
if you're not prepared for them.

188
00:07:35,160 --> 00:07:37,830
Even reliable vehicles
like the Honda Civic

189
00:07:37,830 --> 00:07:40,590
will eventually need repairs
beyond normal maintenance.

190
00:07:40,590 --> 00:07:43,140
This is exactly why you
need an emergency fund

191
00:07:43,140 --> 00:07:45,570
of three to five months
of your living expenses.

192
00:07:45,570 --> 00:07:48,630
Without it, a single
major repair can derail

193
00:07:48,630 --> 00:07:50,250
your entire financial plan.

194
00:07:50,250 --> 00:07:53,940
With cars, it's not a matter
of if something will break,

195
00:07:53,940 --> 00:07:54,773
it's when.

196
00:07:54,773 --> 00:07:57,647
So let's add all this up.

197
00:07:57,647 --> 00:07:58,770
Drum roll please.
(drums beating)

198
00:07:58,770 --> 00:08:03,770
Your affordable $27,867 Honda Civic

199
00:08:04,140 --> 00:08:05,773
actually costs you $46,821

200
00:08:09,240 --> 00:08:10,230
over five years,

201
00:08:10,230 --> 00:08:12,180
but it gets even worse than this

202
00:08:12,180 --> 00:08:15,032
as this doesn't even
consider opportunity cost.

203
00:08:15,032 --> 00:08:17,490
(eerie music)

204
00:08:17,490 --> 00:08:19,470
This is where it gets really painful.

205
00:08:19,470 --> 00:08:21,300
Let's look at a five year comparison

206
00:08:21,300 --> 00:08:23,400
between someone that chooses the car

207
00:08:23,400 --> 00:08:25,290
and someone that chooses to invest.

208
00:08:25,290 --> 00:08:28,560
If you decide to choose the
new Honda Civic in our example,

209
00:08:28,560 --> 00:08:29,850
then after five years,

210
00:08:29,850 --> 00:08:31,747
you'll only be left with $19,295.

211
00:08:35,040 --> 00:08:37,260
This is, of course,
after reselling the car

212
00:08:37,260 --> 00:08:39,060
at its current market value.

213
00:08:39,060 --> 00:08:41,070
That's assuming it's been well maintained

214
00:08:41,070 --> 00:08:42,300
with minimal damage.

215
00:08:42,300 --> 00:08:45,990
That's a loss of over
$27,000 in net worth.

216
00:08:45,990 --> 00:08:47,640
No wonder it's such a wealth killer.

217
00:08:47,640 --> 00:08:49,290
However, if you choose to take

218
00:08:49,290 --> 00:08:52,380
that same $780 monthly payment

219
00:08:52,380 --> 00:08:55,020
and stick it into an S&P 500 index fund

220
00:08:55,020 --> 00:08:57,240
based on the historical average return

221
00:08:57,240 --> 00:08:59,100
of around 10% per year,

222
00:08:59,100 --> 00:09:02,650
after five years, you'd
have approximately $60,016.

223
00:09:05,100 --> 00:09:08,280
Of course, past results can't
guarantee future returns.

224
00:09:08,280 --> 00:09:11,310
However, if it followed the
same historical pattern,

225
00:09:11,310 --> 00:09:15,090
then that would be gain of
over $13,000 in net worth.

226
00:09:15,090 --> 00:09:17,287
That's a price difference of $40,721.

227
00:09:21,150 --> 00:09:23,730
That means by choosing
the car over investing,

228
00:09:23,730 --> 00:09:26,490
you could be giving up $40,000 of wealth.

229
00:09:26,490 --> 00:09:29,340
Most people repeat this
cycle every few years

230
00:09:29,340 --> 00:09:31,140
for their entire work in lives.

231
00:09:31,140 --> 00:09:33,990
This is just one example of
putting your money to work.

232
00:09:33,990 --> 00:09:36,630
You could choose to invest
in starting a side hustle,

233
00:09:36,630 --> 00:09:38,130
buying a rental property,

234
00:09:38,130 --> 00:09:40,440
or even launching your
own full blown business.

235
00:09:40,440 --> 00:09:42,660
The key is getting your
money working for you

236
00:09:42,660 --> 00:09:43,920
instead of against you.

237
00:09:43,920 --> 00:09:47,100
That's not even mentioning
individual stocks and crypto,

238
00:09:47,100 --> 00:09:49,380
although they are riskier investments.

239
00:09:49,380 --> 00:09:50,970
But to put it into perspective,

240
00:09:50,970 --> 00:09:54,810
if you'd invested that same $46,821

241
00:09:54,810 --> 00:09:57,210
in Microsoft stock five years ago

242
00:09:57,210 --> 00:09:58,740
instead of the Honda Civic,

243
00:09:58,740 --> 00:10:02,070
you'd have seen a 224% total return.

244
00:10:02,070 --> 00:10:06,150
Turning your money into
over $150,000 today.

245
00:10:06,150 --> 00:10:07,950
Think about that for a second.

246
00:10:07,950 --> 00:10:11,340
The same money that bought
you a depreciating car

247
00:10:11,340 --> 00:10:13,230
could have bought you a small fortune

248
00:10:13,230 --> 00:10:15,750
in one of the world's
most successful companies.

249
00:10:15,750 --> 00:10:18,120
The point isn't that you
should never own a car.

250
00:10:18,120 --> 00:10:21,900
It's that every financial
decision has an opportunity cost.

251
00:10:21,900 --> 00:10:23,580
Every dollar tied up in something

252
00:10:23,580 --> 00:10:25,470
that loses value is a dollar

253
00:10:25,470 --> 00:10:27,450
that's not compounding in your favor.

254
00:10:27,450 --> 00:10:29,550
You might be thinking, "If this is true,

255
00:10:29,550 --> 00:10:31,440
then why aren't more people investing?"

256
00:10:31,440 --> 00:10:33,180
And to be honest, I think it's

257
00:10:33,180 --> 00:10:35,520
because they don't understand
how to actually do it.

258
00:10:35,520 --> 00:10:37,890
Back in my day, it used
to be very difficult

259
00:10:37,890 --> 00:10:39,660
as you had to phone up a stockbroker.

